In [21]:
homophily_total = {}
for i in range (0,5000):
    nodes_shuffle = politics_nodes.political_ideology.sample(frac=1).reset_index(drop=True)
    nodes_shuffle
    G_dict = dict(zip(politics_nodes.Id, nodes_shuffle))
    nx.set_node_attributes(G, G_dict, 'political_ideology')
    mixed_edges=0
    for m,n in G.edges():
            if ((G.nodes[m]['political_ideology'] == 'neutral' and G.nodes[n]['political_ideology'] != 'neutral') or (G.nodes[m]['political_ideology'] == 'neutral' and G.nodes[n]['political_ideology'] != 'neutral')):
                mixed_edges += 1
    homophily = homophily1-(mixed_edges/441)
    homophily_total[i]=homophily
homophily_total

5000 rows × 2 columns

Based on the data, I can conclude that the predicted homophily value is more or less likely to be the same as the expected homophily value.

The Walsh dataset contains information about a set of political books available in its database. These books can be categorized as neutral, conservative or liberal in their political ideologies. My goal was to determine the number of commonalities between these two distinct viewpoints that are addressed in the political books available in the network. Using the predetermined labels of each book title, I used an if statement to establish which category each book should be assigned.

Originally, there were only two political categories: conservative and liberal. However, after analyzing the data, I realized that there was an additional category: politically neutral. In order to compensate for this additional category, I merged the conservative and the liberal books into a non-neutral category. This resulted in neutral versus non-neutral ideological political books. Unfortunately, this technique sacrifices the original categories of liberal and conservative ideologies, as they are now one category. However, this had to be done because the homophily formula does not support more than 2 categories.

In [65]:
def neighborhood_overlap(g, u, v):
    n_common_nbrs = len(set(nx.common_neighbors(g, u, v)))
    n_join_nbrs = g.degree(u) + g.degree(v) - n_common_nbrs - 2
    return n_common_nbrs / n_join_nbrs

After writing additional code, there is very little overlap among the liberal, conservative and neutral labels in the graph. Specifically, there is an average sized overlap between the political ideology nodes and the Girvan Newman partition nodes. There appears to be no logical reason to explain this kind of overlap. In my opinion, the Girvan Newman community detection appears to be more accurate because the numbers in a political ideology size and a Girvan Newman partition size are relatively the same. For example, if there are 45 liberal labels, the Girvan Newman partition algorithm would classify about 43 of those labels into a single partition.

Given the Girvan-Newman communities, Louvain communities and the original political ideology labels, many similarities and differences can be found among them all. All three visualizations have nodes grouped together based on a specific attribute, which can be a Girvan-Newman partition, Louvain partition or its political ideology. All three visualizations also are laid out in the spring position. More specifically, the Girvan-Newman and original political ideology visualizations have the same number (3) colors that represent a partition or a political ideology respectively.

The only difference among the three visualizations can be found between the Louvain and original political ideology representations. The Louvain visualization has 5 colors due to its 5 partitions (based on the Louvain community detection algorithm), whereas the original political ideology visualization has 3 colors based on the node’s original 3 categories.

In my opinion, these match my findings from question 2. By adding two extra categories/colors in the Louvain communities, the data becomes harder to understand and more skewed. Meaning, they do not correctly line up with the original three categories, which is what our initial network is based. Therefore, the Girvan-Newman based approach remains true to the original data/question, thus creating a more accurate visualization.

4.¶

Because the Girvan-Newman visualization most accurately represents the data, I have chosen to summarize the community structure of its graph. This graph does not exhibit homophily because all of the nodes are split into 3 groups, with little to no nodes of different groups being connected. There are only a handful of edges that connect two nodes of different groups. This is most likely because liberals and conservatives have vastly different political viewpoints. While using the information in the Gavin-Newman visualization, I can look at a node’s color and easily associate it with original political ideology.
